on investment on your time and your efforts? Well 
I kind of figured that was a better title and for

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:40.000
anybody that knows me, it kind of sounds more 
like me as well. So tonight we're going to talk

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:47.520
about how you can get a return on investment on 
your time and your efforts with accessibility and

00:06:47.520 --> 00:06:55.680
how you can then also have a good way to explain 
accessibility to your clients, so that they also

00:06:55.680 --> 00:07:02.400
can see the return on investment for bringing 
accessibility into all of their digital products

00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:08.800
and their company. So first off just of course we 
all know this, but we're just going to touch on it,

00:07:08.800 --> 00:07:14.160
but what is accessibility? Accessibility is 
removing the barriers that prevent people from

00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:21.280
having access, equal access whether it's a building, 
an area, a service that's being provided, a website

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:29.440
an app, any digital product. And accessibility is 
taking that initiative to create products that are

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:37.600
usable by, with people, by people, with the widest 
possible range of abilities. What some people may

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:45.360
not know, is when you think accessibility first, and 
think about making things accessible to all people,

00:07:45.360 --> 00:07:56.400
you open so many avenues, so many possibilities, so 
much creativity and innovation, that accessibility

00:07:56.400 --> 00:08:02.080
creates good growth in a lot of ways. 
And I'll touch on some of those tonight.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.000
What is web accessibility specifically? We have seen

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:16.160
the wA11y, sometimes the w is out there, it's just 
the A 1 1 y and what that means is that between

00:08:17.280 --> 00:08:22.560
the A and the y there is actually 11 letters 
that should be in there, because it spells out

00:08:22.560 --> 00:08:29.200
the entire word, accessibility. We put the W 
in there for web, so when you see wAlly or

00:08:29.200 --> 00:08:34.720
Ally, whichever way you want to pronounce 
this, it's accessibility. It's about people.

00:08:35.600 --> 00:08:41.120
It's about making a difference. So web 
accessibility refers to the website that is

00:08:41.120 --> 00:08:49.360
designed for everyone! We want everyone, regardless 
of their ability or disability, to have the same

00:08:49.360 --> 00:08:57.280
ease of access. That's the most important part. It's 
the user experience that everybody gets to have.

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:05.520
So we also have to keep in mind that web 
accessibility, it actually involves a wide

00:09:05.520 --> 00:09:11.280
range of disabilities. So many times we hear 
people talk about only screen readers, or

00:09:11.280 --> 00:09:18.160
blind individuals, or somebody needing 
captions without taking into an understanding

00:09:18.160 --> 00:09:25.200
that there are far more areas and ranges 
of disabilities that we need to consider.

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:33.440
So then I get people that say this to me all the 
time, rather sarcastically, they unfortunately do.

00:09:33.440 --> 00:09:39.920
Is there really a need for web accessibility? I
mean, after all how many people really are disabled ?

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:46.720
I'm in the United States, so some of the figures 
and facts that I will present this evening are

00:09:46.720 --> 00:09:52.560
based on my area. But since this is global I 
also am going to show some figures and I'll

00:09:52.560 --> 00:10:00.000
make comments on some other countries as well.
Because accessibility is international.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:07.200
In the United States, 25.6 percent of adults in the 
United States have some type of disability .

00:10:07.200 --> 00:10:12.800
And that number fluctuates, because there are 
disabilities that individuals are born with,

00:10:12.800 --> 00:10:19.120
there are disabilities that people suddenly 
get because of an accident or an illness,

00:10:19.120 --> 00:10:30.080
or surgery. There's disabilities that come with 
age. So that number is not just 25.6 percent.

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:36.080
It's really a fluctuating number that 
could affect every single one of us.

00:10:38.400 --> 00:10:45.520
Around the world there are more than one billion 
people living with some form of disability.

00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:50.560
So when someone says, is there really a need for web 
accessibility, is there really people that need it?

00:10:50.560 --> 00:10:57.040
I kind of think there is. I kind of think that 
it's important that we take a look at what

00:10:57.040 --> 00:11:04.960
I know to be an invisible segment of our society. 
When I ask people why their site is not accessible

00:11:04.960 --> 00:11:10.400
or why they don't consider accessibility, they 
don't think they have ever seen or know anybody,

00:11:10.400 --> 00:11:16.000
but maybe that guy that just passed him in the 
hallway, that might have a disability. They don't

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:23.440
consider how many people they're overlooking. 
It's an invisible segment of our society that we

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:30.720
need to bring visible. And it's not them versus us.
It's not one group versus another. It's all of us,

00:11:31.280 --> 00:11:39.360
it's all of us collectively that make up this 
group. People with disabilities are in a community

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:46.480
that makes up a whole lot more than just the 
single individual, because it's their families,

00:11:47.040 --> 00:11:53.440
their communities, their friends, the people 
that they do business with, the people that

00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:59.680
they interact with, it's a very powerful consumer 
base. And if a company has a website and they're

00:11:59.680 --> 00:12:06.800
not accessible, they're missing out on this very 
powerful base. So then the next question comes up.

00:12:06.800 --> 00:12:12.240
Is there really a problem? I mean after all, 
how big a problem, if there is one, how big is it?

00:12:12.240 --> 00:12:20.400
So for those of you that are familiar, there's a 
company WebA I M, and every year they do an audit on

00:12:20.400 --> 00:12:29.440
the home page only, of one million sites. And for 
2019, actually I correct myself, February of 2020

00:12:30.240 --> 00:12:37.840
they did their million sites evaluation 
and what showed up was, 98.1 %

00:12:38.560 --> 00:12:45.680
of all the sites they tested had errors, 
had barriers to people with disabilities.

00:12:46.320 --> 00:12:55.760
Ninety-eight point one percent of the sites they tested out of one million, 
less than 2% were fully accessible.

00:12:56.800 --> 00:13:02.080
And I put on the screen that big number because 
I want people to see that number. I want it to be

00:13:02.080 --> 00:13:08.000
important. I want it to, to let it be known that there 
is an opportunity for us as web designers to

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:14.720
make a difference. It's a huge opportunity and the 
source link to that is at the bottom of the screen.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:22.160
But are there other problems with the lack 
of web accessibility? I mean other than just

00:13:23.200 --> 00:13:24.413
WebAIMS one million report? Absolutely, because 
of the lack of web accessibility we are seeing

00:13:24.413 --> 00:13:36.960
one million report? Absolutely, because 
of the lack of web accessibility we are seeing a drastic increase in web accessibility 
lawsuits. As Joe mentioned, I work with

00:13:37.520 --> 00:13:45.840
clients who are referred to me by attorneys. 
Since Covid started, my phone, my email, people

00:13:45.840 --> 00:13:51.600
contacting me because they've received demand 
letters, attorneys contacting me inquiring about

00:13:51.600 --> 00:13:57.360
what can be done for their client. It has 
tripled. I can't handle all of these people.

00:13:58.880 --> 00:14:04.640
So far we're doing a good job at either working 
with them or referring them out, but that is a huge

00:14:04.640 --> 00:14:12.960
increase just for me. So this is not going to 
go away. Whether it's Covid where people are

00:14:12.960 --> 00:14:18.160
now, everyone is in their home and relying upon 
the internet, or whether it's going to be after

00:14:18.160 --> 00:14:25.200
Covid, when it becomes real obvious that 
everyone deserves the right to equal access

00:14:26.080 --> 00:14:34.480
everywhere, including the web. And personally 
I appreciate that there's a tension being

00:14:34.480 --> 00:14:39.200
brought to the lack of web accessibility, 
I just don't care for these trolls at all.

00:14:40.160 --> 00:14:48.960
So the more that we make websites accessible, the 
more these trolls, is going to make their efforts

00:14:48.960 --> 00:14:57.840
more difficult and that's a goal of mine. Here's 
an interesting piece of information from the

00:14:58.640 --> 00:15:07.200
report from WebAIM. The top six common types 
of WCAG 2 failures on these sites that they

00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:15.760
tested, look at this. Low contrast text, 86 percent point three of pages had

00:15:16.480 --> 00:15:23.040
low contrast text. Earlier today there was 
a presentation about colours and contrast.

00:15:23.040 --> 00:15:29.280
So hopefully you attended that particular 
presentation. If not, when these videos are

00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:35.280
available, I do hope that you go back and you 
watch and listen to what Colleen had to say.

00:15:36.160 --> 00:15:42.880
Right at the top, Low Contrast. Personally, 
I don't understand why people put gray

00:15:42.880 --> 00:15:48.160
font on a light gray background. That's never 
made sense to me, but I see that on so many sites,  and obviously WebAIM

00:15:51.040 --> 00:15:56.400
found something similar. The 
other one, Missing alternative text for images, 66 %.

00:15:57.280 --> 00:16:01.520
Come on, that's like the one 
thing we talk about the most.

00:16:03.680 --> 00:16:06.720
Empty links, Missing form fields, Empty buttons,

00:16:07.360 --> 00:16:13.040
Missing the document language? We're not even going 
to tell people what the language of the website is?

00:16:15.120 --> 00:16:21.280
How easy if you had a website that had 
these six errors, they came to you, how

00:16:21.280 --> 00:16:27.920
easy would it be for you to remediate that 
site? Keeping that in mind, why aren't they?

00:16:29.120 --> 00:16:33.600
That's my question. Maybe they need you 
to knock on their door and tell them.

00:16:34.640 --> 00:16:41.360
Now at the same time I read legal cases on a 
daily basis. I always tell people if you can't go

00:16:41.360 --> 00:16:46.000
to sleep, something that's better than counting 
sheep is to read some of these legal briefs.

00:16:47.200 --> 00:16:52.320
They're not really entertaining, but they 
are educational and the most common problems

00:16:52.320 --> 00:16:57.760
referred in these cases, the website prevents 
screen readers from accessing primary content.

00:16:58.720 --> 00:17:07.280
Oh boy, here we go again, no text description for 
an image, forms not working, you can't increase

00:17:07.280 --> 00:17:13.360
the text to 200 % without loss of content 
or functionality? Here's one that a lot of people

00:17:13.360 --> 00:17:18.400
don't think about. If you have something on 
your website that has a time limit on it,

00:17:18.960 --> 00:17:26.080
you need to let people have a way to adjust it, 
disable it, slow it down, restart it, instead of

00:17:26.080 --> 00:17:31.840
just timing them out and kicking them off. Because 
a sighted person would see if there's a countdown,

00:17:32.960 --> 00:17:39.040
but perhaps someone with a disability either 
doesn't get the warning, can't read the warning,

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:44.240
can't respond fast enough to the warning, 
because you didn't give them enough time.

00:17:45.440 --> 00:17:51.280
Web pages without titles, oh my goodness. It is so 
easy to put a title in a WordPress site. How could that

00:17:51.280 --> 00:17:58.000
happen, I'm beside myself. The purpose of each link 
cannot be determined from the text link alone,

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:06.400
and that's where we get a whole lot of those, click 
here. And I believe we had someone just a couple of

00:18:06.400 --> 00:18:14.000
presentations previous, that talked about just that. 
Very, very important. So you see that the problems

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:21.040
that are being referenced in lawsuits and the ones 
that WebAIM found are simple to remediate. They're

00:18:21.040 --> 00:18:27.440
simple to put in in the first place, but when you 
have a client come to you with a site that has

00:18:27.440 --> 00:18:34.240
these problems, these are the simple ones to fix. So 
what's the solution to the lack of accessibility?

00:18:34.800 --> 00:18:41.280
Very simple, make products that are accessible to 
everyone out of the gate. We do know that now that

00:18:41.280 --> 00:18:47.360
there are themes within the WordPress repository 
that are accessible ready. I do know there are

00:18:48.080 --> 00:18:53.520
uh people that, that's all they will 
work with, is an accessible ready theme.

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:56.960
And then they make sure that the contents 
and the images and everything they add to

00:18:56.960 --> 00:19:03.680
it remains accessible. They make their job easy.
Remediate products and areas that have barriers,

00:19:05.360 --> 00:19:10.160
support companies and products that are accessible 
and innovate with new products. You may not have

00:19:10.160 --> 00:19:16.640
known, that the disabled market or excuse me the 
disabled community, is actually considered

00:19:17.680 --> 00:19:24.720
to be extreme users of certain products. What that 
means is, what you may not also be aware of is that

00:19:24.720 --> 00:19:30.720
voice recognition software has been available 
for people with disabilities for 20 plus years,

00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:37.840
and because people with disabilities were using 
voice technician, voice recognition technology,

00:19:39.680 --> 00:19:46.080
that same technology is now used in 
Alexa and Siri and Google's assistant.

00:19:46.800 --> 00:19:53.760
So something that was done for a, what was a 
select group of people by their first analysis,

00:19:53.760 --> 00:19:57.280
is something that has now 
been rolled out for everyone.

00:19:58.880 --> 00:20:08.080
So it's not a small group. It's all of us that 
benefit from these products. But let's move into

00:20:08.080 --> 00:20:14.240
what people want to know about tonight and that 
is, the Increased Value of Accessibility for both

00:20:14.240 --> 00:20:20.800
Designers and Companies. What you hear a lot is, 
accessibility can drive innovation, such as what

00:20:20.800 --> 00:20:28.240
I just mentioned, it can enhance your brand or 
hurt it, it helps SEO, it can minimize legal risk

00:20:28.960 --> 00:20:37.280
and it can extend your market reach. And yet, 
those five points to some people are just vague.

00:20:39.680 --> 00:20:47.040
Yeah, maybe, but what about me, what can it do for 
me, for my company or what can it do for me?

00:20:47.600 --> 00:20:53.520
I'm a designer with a small agency, 
what can it do? So I want to remind you,

00:20:56.480 --> 00:21:05.440
if my slides will progress, this 
market, 98.1% of the market needs you,

00:21:07.200 --> 00:21:18.320
for your web accessibility knowledge, expertise 
to go in there and make a difference, 98%. So when

00:21:18.320 --> 00:21:23.920
I hear people tell me, well you know what, I, my 
client doesn't want to pay for accessibility.

00:21:24.800 --> 00:21:37.360
I don't know what to do? Ninety-eight percent of the marketplace 
need you. So if that client doesn't want

00:21:37.920 --> 00:21:44.800
to be inclusive and bring accessibility in 
and you have done your best to educate them,

00:21:46.640 --> 00:21:50.960
maybe you need to turn your attention to 
somebody who will appreciate you and your skills

00:21:51.520 --> 00:21:59.840
and your commitment and your dedication. Just 
saying. But then we come back to, well what can

00:21:59.840 --> 00:22:05.920
I charge? You know I mean, I, I don't know, how can 
I mark this up? How do I make a living doing this?

00:22:07.440 --> 00:22:16.080
When I first had a website made for me it 
was in 1996, 97-ish, the person charged me $3, 000.

00:22:17.920 --> 00:22:22.080
I didn't think anything of it at the 
time, other than, phew, that's a lot of money,

00:22:22.080 --> 00:22:25.840
but I also thought that must be the going rate, 
because I had nothing else to compare it to.

00:22:26.960 --> 00:22:32.240
But the person that designed my website was not 
very pleased, because I kept asking questions and I

00:22:32.240 --> 00:22:38.560
wanted this little tweak and just that change, and 
can we do this, and let's move that and he made a

00:22:38.560 --> 00:22:43.840
statement one day and said, look I just don't have 
time for all your questions. If you want answers,

00:22:43.840 --> 00:22:51.920
go take a class and get the answers for yourself.
So I did and I never had to ask him another

00:22:51.920 --> 00:22:57.680
question, but I also never had to pay him any more 
money, because I knew how then to do it myself.

00:22:58.400 --> 00:23:05.200
So trust me, I never say that to clients, but 
I look back at that and when I first started

00:23:05.200 --> 00:23:11.120
working websites myself, I knew I couldn't 
charge $3,000. I didn't have

00:23:11.120 --> 00:23:19.120
that much intelligence, expertise, information, 
experience, even though I'd just taken a class.

00:23:19.920 --> 00:23:26.240
I didn't think I could and I didn't. So I came up 
with a value calculator and here's where if you

00:23:26.240 --> 00:23:31.360
have a pen or pencil handy or you take notes on a 
notepad or something, I'd like you to consider this.

00:23:32.320 --> 00:23:37.600
When you think about what is your value when 
you include accessibility into your services,

00:23:39.760 --> 00:23:44.800
what do you charge for a basic website 
prior to adding any accessibility to it?

00:23:45.680 --> 00:23:53.760
Put down that figure. Now I want you to consider 
your personal value. If you have taken classes on

00:23:53.760 --> 00:24:02.800
accessibility, put a plus. If you have certificates 
or degrees, put a plus. If you have any business

00:24:02.800 --> 00:24:08.800
awards or accolades, whether they're related to 
accessibility or just because you have integrity

00:24:08.800 --> 00:24:14.800
and you are a good business person and you take 
care of your clients, give yourself a plus.

00:24:14.800 --> 00:24:19.600
If you are a disabled person yourself or someone 
in your family or a friend that you see often,

00:24:20.480 --> 00:24:27.680
put a plus. If you have employees that are 
disabled that work for you, put a plus. If

00:24:27.680 --> 00:24:33.520
you have an understanding of WCAG for each 
level of understanding, put a plus, or a big plus.

00:24:35.920 --> 00:24:41.840
If you are very in, involved in a particular 
niche market that you know real well,

00:24:42.880 --> 00:24:50.560
you know what the market is, what drives them to 
do what they do in their business, put a plus.

00:24:50.560 --> 00:24:56.800
My niche market is attorneys. It's been attorneys for 
the last 10 and a half years. So I know attorneys.

00:24:56.800 --> 00:25:00.640
I know the legal marketplace, I know what they're 
allowed to do and what they're not allowed to do

00:25:00.640 --> 00:25:06.000
when it comes to marketing and advertising. I am 
always networking with them. So I know that market.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:10.400
If you have a market like that, give yourself a 
plus. Give yourself a plus for every year that

00:25:10.400 --> 00:25:16.640
you already have been including accessibility. 
If you can write code, give yourself a couple

00:25:16.640 --> 00:25:23.920
of big pluses. And if you often network with other 
accessibility professionals, give yourself a plus.

00:25:25.520 --> 00:25:31.520
And then think about what else sets you 
apart from everyone else. That is a huge plus.

00:25:33.760 --> 00:25:38.320
When you look at all those pluses you're going to 
put a dollar amount to that, not with me tonight,

00:25:38.320 --> 00:25:42.800
but at a time when you're going to sit down, 
because this is something that is personal to you.

00:25:43.520 --> 00:25:48.560
Not what everybody else is charging, but what 
is your value. When you understand your value

00:25:48.560 --> 00:25:54.560
you can explain it to your clients and that's 
the important part. So you start with that value,

00:25:55.440 --> 00:26:02.400
then you go to something where it requires 
manual efforts. This is an excerpt, a clipping from

00:26:02.400 --> 00:26:08.560
one of the checklists that we use in my office. 
And it's a spreadsheet that has on the left column

00:26:08.560 --> 00:26:14.960
whatever action that we need to take in order to 
remediate a site, who's going to do that, is that

00:26:14.960 --> 00:26:19.920
person someone that works internal in my company 
or do we have to outsource, and what is the cost.

00:26:20.640 --> 00:26:26.800
Every person that works on a project, if they're 
internal, they have either a salary or a negotiated

00:26:26.800 --> 00:26:32.800
amount that they are paid. If we outsource it, we 
are paying whatever they tell us is their value

00:26:32.800 --> 00:26:40.400
to do that for us. We go down the list and we 
make sure that we cover all our bases. We do test

00:26:40.400 --> 00:26:49.840
everything on JAWS and N V D A by a native user of 
that. When we are remediating images we don't just

00:26:50.720 --> 00:26:55.680
throw in the alt description and call it a day. We 
research and maybe we have to find them a new

00:26:55.680 --> 00:27:01.040
image if the one that is on their site is really 
not that great. Maybe it needs editing, because it's

00:27:01.040 --> 00:27:06.320
too pixelated, maybe it's too big, maybe it doesn't 
fit the content? We're going to change the meta

00:27:06.320 --> 00:27:14.160
info and the geo info for search and we're going 
to do all that, because we go the extra effort.

00:27:14.160 --> 00:27:19.360
What we're doing for our client is more than 
just fixing the technical problems, we want

00:27:19.360 --> 00:27:25.360
a good user experience for them as our client and 
their website for their users and their visitors.

00:27:25.360 --> 00:27:34.080
So think about this type of an effort and what 
value would you put into each one of those? How

00:27:34.080 --> 00:27:39.840
would you separate yourself from everyone 
else? A lot of times people calculate an

00:27:39.840 --> 00:27:45.120
hourly rate. I talked to someone this week who 
told me he came to me and asked me if I'd hire

00:27:45.120 --> 00:27:50.320
him, because he couldn't afford to be freelance 
anymore. So I looked at what he charged a client

00:27:50.320 --> 00:27:55.520
to work on a website and how many extra hours got 
thrown in that he didn't calculate. The end of the

00:27:55.520 --> 00:28:01.840
day, he was making less than $7 an hour.
So in Southern California you can't live on that.

00:28:02.720 --> 00:28:09.120
So I told him, if you're going to calculate 
your value by an hourly rate, ask yourself,

00:28:09.760 --> 00:28:20.160
what is your resentment number. What is the lowest 
amount you would ever allow a client to say

00:28:20.880 --> 00:28:26.000
This is how much I'll pay you per hour and 
take that number and multiply it by four.

00:28:27.040 --> 00:28:33.920
You should never work at a level that causes 
you to not enjoy the work that you're doing,

00:28:33.920 --> 00:28:39.680
because accessibility can be a whole lot of 
fun. The people that you will meet, the clients

00:28:39.680 --> 00:28:47.280
when they get excited, it's just fun. And then 
you have more value, updates and maintenance

00:28:47.280 --> 00:28:51.920
plans. In a lot of the settlements we're seeing, 
in these legal cases, they're asking the court

00:28:52.720 --> 00:28:58.880
to require that people test their sites every 
six months. That's a maintenance plan for you.

00:28:59.680 --> 00:29:06.720
So that's how you add value, that's how you add 
more to you. Your total value then becomes your

00:29:06.720 --> 00:29:12.800
unique value, your cost per hour, your team that 
you work with, the complexity of the site that

00:29:12.800 --> 00:29:19.760
you're going to be working on, and how well your 
skills and expertise can do that, the timeline.

00:29:19.760 --> 00:29:28.400
Rush jobs always cost more and future offerings, 
your your updates and your maintenance plans.

00:29:30.240 --> 00:29:37.680
Then you put that into a strategy. When I first 
started in business in the 80s, long time ago,

00:29:38.560 --> 00:29:45.760
I was out in my neighborhood asking businesses why 
were they successful and the guy next door wasn't?

00:29:45.760 --> 00:29:50.160
Why did they continually succeed when people 
across the street kept going out of business?

00:29:50.720 --> 00:29:56.960
And what I heard more times from the successful 
business, is they had a plan. They didn't wing it.

00:29:57.600 --> 00:30:03.520
They put in a plan and they planned it out 
as far as they could. They put in that plan,

00:30:04.160 --> 00:30:08.640
not only the type of customers and clients 
they wanted, they put in that plan the type

00:30:08.640 --> 00:30:14.320
of education they may need in order to 
satisfy those clients, they put in that plan

00:30:15.120 --> 00:30:23.840
what would happen if business really picked up.
So many people plan in the minute and worry about

00:30:23.840 --> 00:30:30.000
something going wrong, but as I said a couple 
seconds ago, my phone calls and my emails have

00:30:31.280 --> 00:30:36.560
really exploded in the last few months. Fortunately I, have a list of people that I can call upon,

00:30:37.360 --> 00:30:42.400
that I'm able to make sure that that those 
contacts and those inquiries were taken care of.

00:30:43.120 --> 00:30:47.600
Take the information about your value, 
your expertise, what kind of websites

00:30:47.600 --> 00:30:53.280
you want to work on, and what you want to do, 
and put it into a plan and follow that plan.

00:30:55.200 --> 00:30:58.000
Be transparent with your 
client but don't be invisible.

00:30:59.440 --> 00:31:04.880
What we do for our clients, is we either work in 
Basecamp or Asana. We work in Slack and Toggl

00:31:05.520 --> 00:31:11.360
and we give our clients reports all the time. 
They know exactly what we're doing for them, so

00:31:11.360 --> 00:31:16.800
they don't have to worry. And what we do, is we 
audit their website and we give them a report.

00:31:17.520 --> 00:31:23.040
And we may audit that website with an 
automatic tester, before we put our hands

00:31:23.040 --> 00:31:28.880
on it and manually test it, and we will give them 
that report, but then we make sure that they see

00:31:29.520 --> 00:31:34.960
the difference it makes with someone who is 
keyboard only, and someone who is screen reader.

00:31:36.160 --> 00:31:40.800
That way they get a better understanding of 
their target market. They get a better personal

00:31:40.800 --> 00:31:47.680
understanding of accessibility. I have been working 
with accessibility and websites for 12 years,

00:31:47.680 --> 00:31:54.240
maybe a little bit longer and I was brought to my 
knees humbly, at that point. I had been designing

00:31:54.240 --> 00:31:59.840
websites and I thought I was doing a great job. 
I thought I was really proud of what I had,

00:32:00.400 --> 00:32:07.440
and then a member of my family who is blind had
the benefit of someone coming to show her how to

00:32:07.440 --> 00:32:14.560
use a screen reader to access the web and visit 
websites. I was emotionally blown away by how much

00:32:14.560 --> 00:32:21.200
freedom it gave her, but I also was humbled when I 
gave the man my URLS of the sites I was so proud

00:32:21.200 --> 00:32:27.840
of and asked him to test them. And not a single 
one of them could be read by a screen reader.

00:32:29.520 --> 00:32:35.040
My world changed that day. And so I'm hoping 
that as you get accustomed to accessibility,

00:32:35.040 --> 00:32:39.920
your world takes a shift and you shift to 
where this just becomes part of what you do,

00:32:39.920 --> 00:32:44.480
don't even have to think about it. So after you 
get the test and you find out what you're doing

00:32:45.280 --> 00:32:50.320
and you start working with your client, please 
do the easy stuff first and the reason for this

00:32:50.320 --> 00:32:55.120
is, if you are working on the most difficult part 
of the website where you possibly have to write

00:32:55.120 --> 00:33:00.000
some new code and redesign certain things, 
your client doesn't see what you're doing.

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:05.680
He doesn't see that you're making any sort 
of progress at all, but if you go through the

00:33:05.680 --> 00:33:11.120
little things first or what I call the easy 
things, not little, they're all important, the

00:33:11.920 --> 00:33:17.040
easiest things first and then show your 
client as you go along. Your client sees

00:33:17.040 --> 00:33:22.000
progress. Your client sees hope and knows 
that you're doing what you'd promised to do.

00:33:23.760 --> 00:33:30.400
We always follow the WCAG, the checklist. I 
have this spreadsheet on the screen that shows

00:33:30.400 --> 00:33:36.240
the guidelines and where they fall on the WCAG, 
and all of our spreadsheets we reference not only

00:33:36.240 --> 00:33:42.640
with internally to each other, but to our clients, 
which web content accessibility guidelines success

00:33:42.640 --> 00:33:49.200
criteria we are meeting for them. They don't care, 
but they do care that we tell them. They don't

00:33:49.200 --> 00:33:55.280
understand it, but they care that we tell them and 
that's the transparency of it. And that's what's

00:33:55.280 --> 00:34:02.400
important. Plus when you follow the WCAG you learn 
the WCAG. When you do this, the simple stuff first

00:34:03.520 --> 00:34:10.160
you learn. It's easier to learn. So basically you 
can have an increased profit with your business

00:34:10.800 --> 00:34:16.560
by increasing your value to your client, increasing 
in the fees that you're going to charge them,

00:34:16.560 --> 00:34:21.200
because of the value of what you're bringing to 
the table. This will increase your business income

00:34:22.320 --> 00:34:28.480
and unless you go out and buy a brand new Ferrari, 
it should be an increase in your profit. But I

00:34:28.480 --> 00:34:33.920
want you to notice that one thing I didn't say, I 
didn't talk about plug-ins as part of this process,

00:34:33.920 --> 00:34:38.800
because it's good bad and ugly with WordPress. The 
good is there's plugins that can do work for you.

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:44.240
The bad is, a lot of those plugins will make the 
site worse and you're now going to have to figure

00:34:44.240 --> 00:34:49.360
out how to remediate over the plugin that you 
just installed. And the ugly is that there are

00:34:49.360 --> 00:34:53.120
plugins that through their marketing efforts 
are going to try to tell you that they'll do

00:34:53.120 --> 00:35:02.000
your job for you. And then when they don't, 
you're the one that's in trouble. So don't be

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:08.000
the bad apple. Be willing to put in the effort.
You will enjoy it, you'll get excited, trust me.

00:35:10.240 --> 00:35:12.480
Now we'll get to the second half and I promise

00:35:14.160 --> 00:35:17.920
that this is a good part of it that 
you'll be able to share with your clients.

00:35:18.480 --> 00:35:23.600
The Profitability for Companies. People 
with disabilities are not a solitary market.

00:35:23.600 --> 00:35:28.800
They are surrounded by family members and 
friends. They recognize products and services

00:35:28.800 --> 00:35:38.400
that accommodate people in society. They will 
refer to people when it is an accessible website.

00:35:41.440 --> 00:35:45.440
So you want to show them the 
money. In the U.S., the total after

00:35:46.080 --> 00:35:52.800
after tax disposable income for working 
age people with a disability is 490

00:35:53.360 --> 00:35:59.360
billion dollars. That's a lot of money.
Discretionary income which is the income that

00:35:59.360 --> 00:36:04.640
they get to spend after they've paid all their 
their debts and their taxes is still 21 billion.

00:36:05.920 --> 00:36:09.920
Most people aren't aware of these numbers. 
You want to share these with your clients.

00:36:11.760 --> 00:36:15.920
Interesting note that we discovered, is that 
individuals with hearing difficulties represent

00:36:15.920 --> 00:36:21.600
the disability category with the greatest amount 
of discretionary income, followed by people with

00:36:21.600 --> 00:36:27.360
vision disabilities. So when you heard about 
captions from Meryl earlier, earlier today

00:36:28.080 --> 00:36:34.560
this shows why that's important. You can explain 
that to your clients. If you're in the U.K. what

00:36:34.560 --> 00:36:44.080
we have there is, internet users are 10.7 million 
or 10.07. Sixty-nine percent of people will leave a site

00:36:45.200 --> 00:36:51.040
if they have a problem with access and they will 
go someplace else. This is called the click-away

00:36:51.040 --> 00:36:57.440
pound report and in my resources I do have a link 
that you can read this entire report and share it

00:36:57.440 --> 00:37:05.440
with your clients. I also have a Nielsen report 
that gives all the information for U.S. companies,

00:37:06.000 --> 00:37:11.680
but the worst case scenario that you can tell 
your clients is that the cost of a lawsuit is far

00:37:11.680 --> 00:37:18.640
greater. An attorney retainer can be up to $5000, the settlement costs the loss of

00:37:18.640 --> 00:37:27.120
work. Those are real figures and I do not lead with 
this with my clients. I lead with the numbers for

00:37:27.120 --> 00:37:33.520
the market that they can reach. If they don't want 
to listen, then I'll bring this part in. But how

00:37:33.520 --> 00:37:40.160
should they market to the disabled community? 
Decide to developing products that meet that

00:37:40.160 --> 00:37:45.600
needs of people with disabilities. They should get 
involved in the community. They also need to employ

00:37:45.600 --> 00:37:51.840
people with disabilities. Inclusive advertising, 
put an accessibility statement on their website,

00:37:51.840 --> 00:37:56.000
because far too many designers think, well I'll 
just go in and tell my client if they make their

00:37:56.000 --> 00:38:02.000
website accessible, that people will flock to 
it. That's not true. It will give a boost to

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:08.800
the SEO in some cases, but they still need to 
do their marketing. It's essential and this is

00:38:08.800 --> 00:38:14.640
the type of marketing that they need to do. If 
they do this marketing, if they do it genuine,

00:38:15.520 --> 00:38:21.760
they will see a return of that marketplace, because 
like any other community, people with disabilities

00:38:21.760 --> 00:38:26.960
do talk about people that treat them right. And 
when you think about your price and your value

00:38:26.960 --> 00:38:32.960
just remember there's always somebody who's 
willing to do it cheaper. So don't cut yourself

00:38:32.960 --> 00:38:38.960
short when you're talking to your clients about 
your value. Make sure that you go for the big value.

00:38:40.080 --> 00:38:44.800
So some of the references are resources that I'll 
share with you, is the automatic accessibility

00:38:44.800 --> 00:38:53.040
checkers that we use. We don't use one more than 
another except, the top two. We love the Deque Axe-Pro Beta,

00:38:53.040 --> 00:38:59.760
because of the type of reports that we can 
give our client and we love the Tenon API which

00:38:59.760 --> 00:39:07.040
you can put in your website, so that you can see as 
you're working what you're doing and what needs to

00:39:07.040 --> 00:39:11.840
be done. So you don't have to wait till something 
is done to go, did I do it right? By putting the

00:39:11.840 --> 00:39:17.760
API on your website for this one, you'll be able 
to watch your progress and learn as you go along.

00:39:18.640 --> 00:39:21.520
Other resources that I mentioned, 
these are places where you can learn

00:39:22.240 --> 00:39:29.920
knowledge: The Web Accessibility Initiative at 
w3.org has a free course on the introduction

00:39:29.920 --> 00:39:34.400
to web accessibility, and you can get a 
certificate for completing that course

00:39:34.400 --> 00:39:40.640
and it is a great course. I've done that course. I
refer people to that course. It's full of knowledge.

00:39:40.640 --> 00:39:47.200
Knowbility, excellent resource, Deque, WebAIM, CSUN,  
University of Illinois, University of Washington,

00:39:47.200 --> 00:39:53.120
the information is available. The educational 
resources are there. If you need to have a

00:39:53.120 --> 00:39:59.520
native user to test, here are three places 
where you can have, you can contract with them

00:39:59.520 --> 00:40:06.400
for someone or gain a referral. Again, Knowibility 
Access Works, Pearson for the blind and CSUN which

00:40:06.400 --> 00:40:13.760
is here in Southern California. Also in my slides 
will be the links and resources to the statistics

00:40:13.760 --> 00:40:18.720
that I quoted for the companies, for the number 
of people in the community and the spending power.

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:26.800
So in summary 98.1 % of websites need remediation.
One in four people have a recognized disability.

00:40:27.520 --> 00:40:34.800
Accessibility is international. It's a right, it's a, 
it's a personal right, it's a civil right. Plan your

00:40:34.800 --> 00:40:41.680
design to include accessibility, have a strategy 
for remediation, understand the why and how of your

00:40:41.680 --> 00:40:48.480
value to a client, understand the potential market 
so you can explain it to your client. Check the

00:40:48.480 --> 00:40:55.760
obvious and fix those first, fonts, structure, colour 
schemes, video, audio. Don't rely only on automatic

00:40:55.760 --> 00:41:01.680
testers. Test your site manually. Have a native 
user of accessibility technology test your site.

00:41:02.320 --> 00:41:09.040
Be transparent with your clients and support 
the community. And I know I talked fast. I wanted

00:41:09.040 --> 00:41:14.080
to give you a lot of information and since I
know we're being recorded you can come back

00:41:16.080 --> 00:41:21.360
and visit this information again. But I do believe 
if there are questions, maybe I have a couple

00:41:21.360 --> 00:41:24.171
minutes to answer questions.

00:41:24.171 --> 00:41:27.920
[Joe] Yes you do, thank you 
so much Sumner. What a great presentation, thank you.

00:41:29.600 --> 00:41:36.240
All right, let me refresh here. Our first question is, 
Is there a study answering the following

00:41:36.240 --> 00:41:41.251
question: How many people leave a web page because 
of accessibility failure?

00:41:41.251 --> 00:41:45.331
[Sumner] Sixty-seven percent. It's in the pound away report.

00:41:45.331 --> 00:41:45.845
[Joe] Okay

00:41:45.845 --> 00:41:54.667
[Sumner] And the report also indicates that 
when people leave that website they don't give up, they do spend that money elsewhere. So it's a total 
loss.

00:41:54.667 --> 00:42:06.640
[Joe} All right, do you feel designer and developer reluctance in folding in accessibility is that 
they undercharge or overestimate their bottom line? How would you recommend they address 
this or can you share a brief experience?

00:42:07.840 --> 00:42:10.800
[Sumner] My recommendation would be that they

00:42:13.280 --> 00:42:20.160
go through that list of what I did for value and 
accept more about what their personal value is as

00:42:20.160 --> 00:42:26.960
a designer. And if they've undervalued themselves, 
this is so, this is probably a personal issue that

00:42:26.960 --> 00:42:31.680
they need to take and look at. And they might want 
to sit and work with someone. I sit with designers

00:42:31.680 --> 00:42:36.720
all the time that want to discuss, how can I 
increase what I charge? I don't know what my assets are?

00:42:36.720 --> 00:42:42.640
So if, if a person will take a list of what 
are their personal assets, like the list I rang off

00:42:42.640 --> 00:42:48.000
and then reevaluate. What does happen, is many 
times they don't charge enough, they get burned out.

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:53.840
And then it becomes resentment and that doesn't 
work, but at the same time whatever amount they

00:42:53.840 --> 00:42:57.840
charge you don't want to overcharge because 
you're going to have to live up to that amount.

00:42:58.480 --> 00:43:04.640
[Joe] All right, next question, do you think 
that web development is driven too much by

00:43:04.640 --> 00:43:11.840
developers needing to rapidly solve problems 
defined by business rather than by users?

00:43:15.440 --> 00:43:18.427
[Sumner] Not sure if I understand that question.

00:43:18.427 --> 00:43:26.960
[Joe] Okay, 
let me, let me restate it. Do you think that web development is driven too much by developers 
who are try trying to solve business related

00:43:26.960 --> 00:43:31.680
problems instead of trying to solve the 
problem in terms of how a user would use it?

00:43:32.480 --> 00:43:37.440
[Sumner] So if I understand that correctly, a client's 
going to come to a designer and say I need

00:43:37.440 --> 00:43:43.520
a website built, because I need to sell a product,
instead of I need a website built that's the best

00:43:43.520 --> 00:43:47.594
for user experience so I can get more business.
[Joe] Correct

00:43:47.594 --> 00:43:55.360
[Sumner] Okay, well yeah, clients don't know. We have to educate them. That's what they need from us.They 
need us to say, hey you know what, that's great let

00:43:55.360 --> 00:44:00.320
me help you understand how we can make that that 
dream of yours even bigger and more profitable.

00:44:01.040 --> 00:44:07.840
So we as designers need to also be educators. 
Once we understand it, we can explain it.

00:44:09.440 --> 00:44:15.920
[Joe] All right, this is a really brief one, For the 
non-legal, what is a demand letter? You mentioned

00:44:15.920 --> 00:44:21.233
that in your presentation. What does that mean 
in relation to accessibility?

00:44:21.233 --> 00:44:22.080
[Sumner] Demand letter is,

00:44:23.440 --> 00:44:27.600
it's actually a form letter unfortunately, 
but it comes in on an attorney letterhead

00:44:27.600 --> 00:44:36.560
and it says dear website owner I'm sending you 
this letter because my client a blind user or

00:44:36.560 --> 00:44:42.880
a person with another disability, attempted to 
visit your website and there was barriers that

00:44:42.880 --> 00:44:48.720
prevented this person from equal access. So it's 
important that you contact our office to discuss

00:44:48.720 --> 00:44:56.320
some form of remuneration for the difficulties 
and the problems that our client has endured.

00:44:57.040 --> 00:45:01.440
And that is the precursor to them filing 
a case. They send out the demand letter,

00:45:01.440 --> 00:45:07.440
because they want someone to call and go please 
please please and beg that you don't hurt them. When

00:45:07.440 --> 00:45:14.400
uh most of those demand letters don't turn into 
cases, but many of them do. In either case, it's

00:45:14.400 --> 00:45:17.524
important to consult with an attorney how to 
respond.

00:45:17.524 --> 00:45:30.000
[Joe] Awesome. Okay our final question is, excuse me, if you build a website with accessibility in 
mind and the same site without it what do you

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:34.800
think the the difference in cost would be between 
the two sites in terms of what you can charge?

00:45:38.400 --> 00:45:41.920
That's that's a difficult question. I'm not sure...

00:45:43.440 --> 00:45:47.360
[Sumner] Well, I don't know that I can answer it, because if I 
go back to when I was building sites before I

00:45:47.360 --> 00:45:52.400
knew anything about accessibility and I know 
what I charge then, versus what I charge now,

00:45:53.680 --> 00:46:00.320
I don't know how I would back out all my 
accessibility efforts to try to figure out

00:46:02.080 --> 00:46:04.240
what that would be.

00:46:04.240 --> 00:46:08.560
[Joe] Yeah, yeah I 
was gonna say I wouldn't, I mean

00:46:09.120 --> 00:46:10.814
[Sumner] I, I can't I can't even figure that out.

00:46:10.814 --> 00:46:11.920
[Joe] Yeah, that's a difficult question.

00:46:12.800 --> 00:46:18.560
It reminds me, I used to, I used to speak um at high 
schools um or go to the school when they had the

00:46:18.560 --> 00:46:23.520
parents come to work and there would always be a 
kid who would say, how much do you make, which is,

00:46:24.080 --> 00:46:28.400
I mean it's a random question. I'm not making fun 
of it, but it's a difficult question to quantify,

00:46:28.400 --> 00:46:32.547
because your value is based on that formula you 
talked about.

00:46:32.547 --> 00:46:39.440
[Sumner] Exactly and too many times I see in forum posts and discussion groups where someone 
will say, well okay I'm going to build a five-page

00:46:39.440 --> 00:46:43.440
website for a client, what would you charge? 
Well first off that's not enough information

00:46:43.440 --> 00:46:48.160
to find out what that price would be, but on the 
other hand don't choose somebody else's number.

00:46:49.520 --> 00:46:56.160
Your value and their value are totally 
different and and I, I, I really believe that when

00:46:56.960 --> 00:47:01.200
we get into that thinking pattern where we, 
so what is it I'm bringing to the table here?

00:47:02.080 --> 00:47:07.200
And be real clear of what I'm bringing to the 
table has a big value to this client, because

00:47:07.200 --> 00:47:14.080
no one else is bringing this same value. And I'm 
going to make a difference to this client and

00:47:14.080 --> 00:47:18.720
their website and the user experience that no 
one else is going to do, because they're not me.

00:47:20.480 --> 00:47:21.903
And that and it's not ego, it's confidence.

00:47:21.903 --> 00:47:29.002
